definition.value: An amino tetrasaccharide that is 2-acetamido-2-deoxy-alpha-D-galactopyranosyl-(1->3)-alpha-D-galactopyranosyl-(1->3)-2-acetamido-2-deoxy-D-galactopyranose in which the hydroxy group at position 2 of the central alpha-D-galactopyranosyl moiety has been glycosylated by an alpha-L-fucopyranosyl group.
A mannotriose consisting of an alpha-D-mannopyranose residue and two beta-D-mannopyranose residues joined in sequence by (1->3) and (1->2) glycosidic bonds.

A disaccharide derivative that is 4-O-(D-galactopyranosyl)-D-glucopyranose in which the hydroxy group at position 2 of the galactopyranose moiety has been converted into the corresponding hydrogen sulfate derivative.

A disaccharide consisting of a beta-D-galactopyranose residue joined to a D-xylopyranose residue by a (1->4) glycosidic bond. Used to diagnose hypolactasia (lactose intolerance as a result of lactase deficiency) via presence of D-xylose after cleavage by lactase.
A disaccharide consisting of alpha-D-glucopyranose and D-arabinopyranose residues joined in sequence by a (1->3) glycosidic bond.
A beta-D-Glcp-(1->3)-D-Arap in which the carbon bearing the anomeric hydroxy group has beta configuration.
An L-lysopyranose in which the anomeric centre has alpha- configuration.
A Delta(4)-beta-D-GlcpA-(1->4)-D-Glcp in which the the carbon bearing the anomeric hydroxy group has alpha- configuration.
A disaccharide that is D-glycopyranose in which the hydroxy group at position 3 has been converted into the corresponding alpha-L-fucoside.
A disaccharide that is D-glucopyranose in which the hydroxy group at position 2 has been converted into the corresponding alpha-D-galactopyranoside.

A branched amino oligosaccharide that is an undecasaccharide derivative in which two alpha-L-fucosyl-(1->3)-[N-acetyl-beta-D-galactosaminyl-(1->4)]-N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl-(1->2)-alpha-D-mannosyl tetrasaccharide units are linked (1->3) and (1->6) to the mannose residue of a beta-D-mannosyl-(1->4)-N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl(1->4)-N-acetyl-D-glucosamine trisaccharide.
An amino disaccharide consisting of alpha-D-glucofuranosyl and 2-acetamido-2-deoxy-beta-D-glucopyranose residues joined in sequence by a (1->3) glycosidic bond.
